we're only limited by the laws
of physics and our imagination.

00:37:00.440 --> 00:37:04.040
I think that what we do
about it is-- I mean,

00:37:04.040 --> 00:37:06.290
it's kind of up to, I guess,
whoever's in charge then.

00:37:06.290 --> 00:37:09.680
But I mean, you can think about
all kinds of grandiose notions

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:14.632
of building some kind
of small robotic probe,

00:37:14.632 --> 00:37:16.090
maybe a series of
them, maybe about

00:37:16.090 --> 00:37:18.559
the size of Coke can,
maybe send voyaging at 10%

00:37:18.559 --> 00:37:19.350
the speed of light.

00:37:19.350 --> 00:37:20.725
I think that's
probably something

00:37:20.725 --> 00:37:23.140
we could figure out how to do.

00:37:23.140 --> 00:37:25.685
Maybe it could return
some close-up images.

00:37:25.685 --> 00:37:27.310
You could think about
things like that.

00:37:27.310 --> 00:37:30.380
You can think about building an
even bigger telescope or even

00:37:30.380 --> 00:37:31.380
fleets of telescopes.

00:37:31.380 --> 00:37:33.780
Right now I've been
restricting this conversation,

00:37:33.780 --> 00:37:38.890
just to simplify it, to filled
apertures, big pieces of glass,

00:37:38.890 --> 00:37:39.960
big mirrors in space.

00:37:39.960 --> 00:37:41.410
One of the most
exciting things is

00:37:41.410 --> 00:37:44.000
to go with unfilled apertures,
to use interferometry

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.955
to actually link together kind
of like a hyper-telescope.

00:37:46.955 --> 00:37:49.960
You link together a lot of
small, individual apertures,

00:37:49.960 --> 00:37:52.474
maybe dishes that are
about a meter in size,

00:37:52.474 --> 00:37:53.890
but you get a lot
of them, and you

00:37:53.890 --> 00:37:55.780
get a big, big
baseline stretched out.

00:37:55.780 --> 00:37:57.480
And then you get
enough of that, you

00:37:57.480 --> 00:37:59.880
can get some pretty crazy
surface feature map.

00:37:59.880 --> 00:38:02.010
And you can do things like,
I mean, in simulations

00:38:02.010 --> 00:38:04.370
and looking at Earth
from 10 parsecs, say,

00:38:04.370 --> 00:38:07.565
you can see things like
phytoplankton blooms

00:38:07.565 --> 00:38:08.440
in the Pacific Ocean.

00:38:08.440 --> 00:38:09.680
You can see coastlines.

00:38:09.680 --> 00:38:11.530
You can see mountains.

00:38:11.530 --> 00:38:14.370
You can see nighttime
electric lighting.

00:38:14.370 --> 00:38:15.700
You can see New York City.

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:17.240
You can see LA.

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:18.699
So there's things
that we can think

00:38:18.699 --> 00:38:20.781
of that we could do that
are even more futuristic,

00:38:20.781 --> 00:38:22.120
or we could try to go there.

00:38:22.120 --> 00:38:25.054
But for me, it's not
so much about what

00:38:25.054 --> 00:38:26.970
do we do then, necessarily,
it's just the fact

00:38:26.970 --> 00:38:28.750
that we're kind of
on the cusp of being

00:38:28.750 --> 00:38:30.833
able to do these things,
of being able to find out

00:38:30.833 --> 00:38:34.210
whether or not we're alone for
the first time in the history

00:38:34.210 --> 00:38:37.100
of the biosphere, in four
and a half billion years.

00:38:37.100 --> 00:38:41.130
And I'm actually somewhat
more compelled by the notion

00:38:41.130 --> 00:38:42.860
that we'll look
out there, and we

00:38:42.860 --> 00:38:45.260
aren't going to find
anything like that.

00:38:45.260 --> 00:38:47.735
And I think if
that happens, then

00:38:47.735 --> 00:38:51.591
I don't know if it will really
change the lives of people,

00:38:51.591 --> 00:38:52.840
everyday people on the street.

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:54.230
But I think for people
who think about it,

00:38:54.230 --> 00:38:56.275
it might kind of change
how you look at the world

00:38:56.275 --> 00:38:57.790
and how you look
at your own life

00:38:57.790 --> 00:39:00.160
if you realize that
for, let's say,

00:39:00.160 --> 00:39:02.244
a radius of 500
light years or 300

00:39:02.244 --> 00:39:03.660
light years around
the Earth, this

00:39:03.660 --> 00:39:06.802
is literally the
coolest thing going.

00:39:06.802 --> 00:39:08.760
I think that's a powerful
thing to think about.

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:10.920
And I think if we
had that realization,

00:39:10.920 --> 00:39:12.420
maybe we'd take a
little better care

00:39:12.420 --> 00:39:14.960
of ourselves and our planet.

