AUDIENCE: Sort of
along the same lines,

00:39:18.889 --> 00:39:20.430
I mean, if we're
looking for company,

00:39:20.430 --> 00:39:22.140
it would seem that
something like SETI

00:39:22.140 --> 00:39:24.250
would be more interesting than
looking for other planets that

00:39:24.250 --> 00:39:25.190
happen to have oxygen.

00:39:25.190 --> 00:39:27.160
It might be that all the
cool people out there

00:39:27.160 --> 00:39:28.370
are nitrogen-based
except for us.

00:39:28.370 --> 00:39:28.880
Who knows?

00:39:28.880 --> 00:39:29.000
LEE BILLINGS: Right.

00:39:29.000 --> 00:39:29.435
Yeah, no.

00:39:29.435 --> 00:39:30.434
That's a great question.

00:39:30.434 --> 00:39:33.454
And this is not, in any
way, meant to bash SETI.

00:39:33.454 --> 00:39:34.370
I think SETI is great.

00:39:34.370 --> 00:39:36.110
I think it's
tragically underfunded.

00:39:36.110 --> 00:39:38.735
It's been tragically underfunded
the entirety of its existence.

00:39:38.735 --> 00:39:42.720
And Frank Drake first pointed
a telescope at Epsilon Eridani

00:39:42.720 --> 00:39:44.750
in Taos SETI.

00:39:44.750 --> 00:39:47.290
But the problem with
that is that I think

00:39:47.290 --> 00:39:48.922
we have this really
kind of-- you

00:39:48.922 --> 00:39:51.290
know, the inverse-square
law is a real thing.

00:39:51.290 --> 00:39:53.381
And if you look at
our own emanations,

00:39:53.381 --> 00:39:55.630
people sometimes think that,
oh, if they're out there,

00:39:55.630 --> 00:39:59.040
they already know we're here
because of "I Love Lucy"

00:39:59.040 --> 00:40:00.840
or whatever that's
going out there.

00:40:00.840 --> 00:40:02.470
But I don't think so.

00:40:02.470 --> 00:40:04.832
I think if you look at
how big, at least as far

00:40:04.832 --> 00:40:06.540
as we understand it,
how big the hardware

00:40:06.540 --> 00:40:10.092
has to be to detect that even
just a few light years away,

00:40:10.092 --> 00:40:10.800
I don't think so.

00:40:10.800 --> 00:40:14.550
So the point is is that all
this radio communication,

00:40:14.550 --> 00:40:17.080
or communication
via laser pulses,

00:40:17.080 --> 00:40:19.640
whatever it is, it
requires intentionality.

00:40:19.640 --> 00:40:21.480
It requires someone
saying, huh, I

00:40:21.480 --> 00:40:24.360
don't want to invest billions
of dollars, a lot of treasure,

00:40:24.360 --> 00:40:27.786
a lot of time, into beaming
this message out into space.

00:40:27.786 --> 00:40:29.410
And we're listening
for those messages,

00:40:29.410 --> 00:40:30.310
and I'm not saying
that's bad to do.

00:40:30.310 --> 00:40:31.310
I think we should do it.

00:40:31.310 --> 00:40:34.990
But oxygen in an atmosphere,
this kind of disequilibrium

00:40:34.990 --> 00:40:37.610
we're talking about-- and it
doesn't just have to be oxygen,

00:40:37.610 --> 00:40:38.460
there's other
things we could look

00:40:38.460 --> 00:40:40.246
for-- there's no
intentionality required.

00:40:40.246 --> 00:40:42.370
It's just something that's
a product of metabolism.

00:40:42.370 --> 00:40:43.789
Life exists.

00:40:43.789 --> 00:40:45.580
And as far we know it,
life has to maintain

00:40:45.580 --> 00:40:48.580
its orderly structures,
so it vents byproducts.

00:40:48.580 --> 00:40:50.530
So if you can detect
that in an atmosphere,

00:40:50.530 --> 00:40:52.410
it doesn't really
matter whether or not

00:40:52.410 --> 00:40:55.362
the little green men want to
talk to you, you can find them.

00:40:55.362 --> 00:40:57.945
So that's why I think this is a
little, maybe, more important.

00:41:02.160 --> 00:41:05.014
Shouldn't say more important,
but maybe prioritize that.

00:41:05.014 --> 00:41:06.180
Then we find the cool stuff.

00:41:06.180 --> 00:41:08.924
Then we do the SETI
with the big dishes.

00:41:08.924 --> 00:41:09.740
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:41:09.740 --> 00:41:12.920
I saw that India recently
launched a Mars mission,

00:41:12.920 --> 00:41:15.010
I guess.

00:41:15.010 --> 00:41:16.860
Are other countries or
other space programs

00:41:16.860 --> 00:41:18.680
doing anything interesting?

00:41:18.680 --> 00:41:20.869
LEE BILLINGS: Well,
a guy once told me

00:41:20.869 --> 00:41:22.660
that the best way to
make this stuff happen

00:41:22.660 --> 00:41:26.280
is actually to convince the
Chinese to go out and find

00:41:26.280 --> 00:41:28.270
the nearest 100
potentially habitable

00:41:28.270 --> 00:41:32.820
planets and name them all after
departed emperors and things.

00:41:32.820 --> 00:41:34.470
Right now,
unfortunately, there's

00:41:34.470 --> 00:41:36.450
not a lot of activity
internationally.

00:41:36.450 --> 00:41:38.660
ESA, the European Space
Agency, is doing some things.

00:41:38.660 --> 00:41:40.701
They have some really
exciting missions proposed.

00:41:40.701 --> 00:41:43.330
There's one called
"KEOPS," CHEOPS, "KEOPS."

00:41:43.330 --> 00:41:46.110
There's another
one called PLATO.

00:41:46.110 --> 00:41:49.710
But these are not kind of
"Battlestar Galactica" scale,

00:41:49.710 --> 00:41:51.210
really large missions
that are going

00:41:51.210 --> 00:41:54.400
to be able to bring home
the bacon, so to speak.

00:41:54.400 --> 00:41:56.770
The European Space
Agency was on board

00:41:56.770 --> 00:41:59.080
with NASA for these
terrestrial planet finders

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:01.100
earlier last decade.

00:42:01.100 --> 00:42:03.480
But again, NASA decided we
should go back to the Moon

00:42:03.480 --> 00:42:06.190
instead and keep doing a
few more shuttle flights

00:42:06.190 --> 00:42:06.920
and did that.

00:42:06.920 --> 00:42:09.910
So right now, it
is mostly the US,

00:42:09.910 --> 00:42:11.830
but the US isn't
really doing much.

00:42:11.830 --> 00:42:15.160
No one's really doing a lot.

00:42:15.160 --> 00:42:16.940
AUDIENCE: It's me again.

00:42:16.940 --> 00:42:21.350
So I have a theory.

00:42:21.350 --> 00:42:25.280
It's extremely expensive
to launch things to space,

00:42:25.280 --> 00:42:28.020
especially if we want to
put them in the Lagrange 1

00:42:28.020 --> 00:42:32.754
point, which no one
ever done so far.

00:42:32.754 --> 00:42:34.420
So we don't even know
if we can do that.

00:42:37.650 --> 00:42:40.960
Maybe it's going to be
more efficient to be

00:42:40.960 --> 00:42:42.570
a little bit more
strategic about it

00:42:42.570 --> 00:42:47.450
and invest in ways to deliver
things to space in a cheaper

00:42:47.450 --> 00:42:49.240
fashion, so that
this will be easier

00:42:49.240 --> 00:42:51.100
to bring those big telescopes.

00:42:51.100 --> 00:42:52.725
LEE BILLINGS: No,
you're totally right.

00:42:52.725 --> 00:42:54.480
I mean, the main
cost, the reason

00:42:54.480 --> 00:42:57.295
why these things
cost so much and they

00:42:57.295 --> 00:42:59.420
take so long to develop is
because they can't fail.

00:42:59.420 --> 00:43:00.840
James Webb is a great example.

00:43:00.840 --> 00:43:03.360
Again, it's kind of got the
astrophysics program of NASA

00:43:03.360 --> 00:43:04.984
on the ropes because
it's so expensive.

00:43:04.984 --> 00:43:05.840
It's over budget.

00:43:05.840 --> 00:43:07.590
These things are so
expensive because they

00:43:07.590 --> 00:43:08.881
have to be launched into space.

00:43:08.881 --> 00:43:10.675
They have to be built
to not fail in space.

00:43:10.675 --> 00:43:12.600
They have to be built
to survive the launch.

00:43:12.600 --> 00:43:15.170
And it's just expensive to get
out into space fundamentally,

00:43:15.170 --> 00:43:17.420
especially if you're doing
something like the shuttle.

00:43:17.420 --> 00:43:19.910
I mean, that was
ridiculously expensive.

00:43:19.910 --> 00:43:21.430
If we can bring
launch costs down

00:43:21.430 --> 00:43:24.800
via like an Elon Musk
Space X, things like that,

00:43:24.800 --> 00:43:27.740
or if we can find a way
to maybe build things

00:43:27.740 --> 00:43:31.160
modularly, right,
just like we do

00:43:31.160 --> 00:43:33.540
on ground-based observatories.

00:43:33.540 --> 00:43:36.130
No one assembles
a whole telescope

00:43:36.130 --> 00:43:38.525
in a basement someplace, and
then hikes it up a mountain,

00:43:38.525 --> 00:43:40.400
and puts it up there,
and expects it to work.

00:43:40.400 --> 00:43:42.844
Instead, you build
it on the mountain,

00:43:42.844 --> 00:43:44.510
and you bring it into
alignment, and you

00:43:44.510 --> 00:43:46.101
make it work from there.

00:43:46.101 --> 00:43:47.350
We could do that in space too.

00:43:47.350 --> 00:43:50.069
And there's a guy in the book,
the director of the Space

00:43:50.069 --> 00:43:51.860
Telescope Science
Institute, Matt Mountain,

00:43:51.860 --> 00:43:53.640
who's a very big
proponent of this idea.

00:43:53.640 --> 00:43:56.056
He thinks that it's a good
mission for NASA and for NASA's

00:43:56.056 --> 00:43:59.510
Astronaut Corps to do in
the interim of going to Mars

00:43:59.510 --> 00:44:00.050
or whatever.

00:44:00.050 --> 00:44:02.000
I think it's more exciting
than visiting an asteroid,

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:04.399
personally, if we could build
a big planet-finding space

00:44:04.399 --> 00:44:06.190
telescope up there and
service it in space.

00:44:06.190 --> 00:44:07.500
That's awesome.

00:44:07.500 --> 00:44:08.747
I think we should do that.

00:44:08.747 --> 00:44:10.830
So these are ideas that
everyone's thinking about.

00:44:10.830 --> 00:44:11.920
And I think you're
on the right track

00:44:11.920 --> 00:44:13.580
that we need to get
launch costs down.

00:44:13.580 --> 00:44:16.510
We also need to,
frankly, I think, get

00:44:16.510 --> 00:44:20.030
space science solely out of the
hands of big federal agencies

00:44:20.030 --> 00:44:20.530
probably.

00:44:23.470 --> 00:44:23.970
Anymore?

00:44:27.281 --> 00:44:29.280
AUDIENCE: I think it was
Neil deGrasse Tyson who

00:44:29.280 --> 00:44:31.710
said that if you just
convince the Chinese to launch

00:44:31.710 --> 00:44:35.680
a massive space program, the
US will be on Mars in a decade.

00:44:35.680 --> 00:44:37.830
But you mentioned
earlier that it's

00:44:37.830 --> 00:44:39.350
kind of tough to
get people excited

00:44:39.350 --> 00:44:41.970
about this kind of exploration
because it's so commonplace,

00:44:41.970 --> 00:44:42.470
I think.

00:44:45.270 --> 00:44:46.840
Someone mentioned SETI earlier.

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:49.980
One cool thing they did, maybe
like six or seven years ago,

00:44:49.980 --> 00:44:51.700
was they had this
program run out

00:44:51.700 --> 00:44:54.220
of their institute
in Berkeley, I think,

00:44:54.220 --> 00:44:56.760
where they leveraged
the power of the web

00:44:56.760 --> 00:44:58.740
to get a lot of this
heavy processing.

00:44:58.740 --> 00:45:01.810
And just where they were
lacking the computer power,

00:45:01.810 --> 00:45:05.330
they just set up this proxy
service where people at home

00:45:05.330 --> 00:45:08.220
could volunteer their
computers to help process

00:45:08.220 --> 00:45:11.757
this massive corpus of data
that they were taking in

00:45:11.757 --> 00:45:12.840
from all their satellites.

00:45:12.840 --> 00:45:15.340
LEE BILLINGS: I'm a
SETI@home volunteer.

00:45:15.340 --> 00:45:16.337
So yeah, yeah.

00:45:16.337 --> 00:45:18.420
AUDIENCE: Do you think
we'll ever get to the point

00:45:18.420 --> 00:45:22.380
where if web is giving us
so much more information

00:45:22.380 --> 00:45:24.190
than we can possibly
sift through

00:45:24.190 --> 00:45:27.640
in any reasonable time,
that we could leverage

00:45:27.640 --> 00:45:31.717
the power of the web to help
quicken the search, I guess?

00:45:31.717 --> 00:45:33.300
LEE BILLINGS: That's
a great question,

00:45:33.300 --> 00:45:35.966
and the great part of the answer
is that we're already doing it.

00:45:35.966 --> 00:45:39.870
There's a great program called
Planet Hunters that's-- I mean,

00:45:39.870 --> 00:45:44.360
I think a lot of funding for
it comes through The Planetary

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:47.610
Society, which I recommend
everyone support.

00:45:47.610 --> 00:45:50.020
And this is something that
actually looks at light curves

00:45:50.020 --> 00:45:52.090
from Kepler.

00:45:52.090 --> 00:45:54.570
I mean, we talk about planets
pouring out of the sky.

00:45:54.570 --> 00:45:56.160
I mean, Kepler's
like a fire hose

00:45:56.160 --> 00:45:57.000
that we're all
trying to drink from.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.280
There's so much data
that's coming out of it.

00:45:59.280 --> 00:46:00.870
The telescope's kind of out
of commission right now.

00:46:00.870 --> 00:46:02.280
It had this pointing
error, so it's not even

00:46:02.280 --> 00:46:03.320
delivering a lot of new data.

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:04.980
We're still processing
through, churning

00:46:04.980 --> 00:46:06.521
through all that
data from last year.

00:46:06.521 --> 00:46:08.160
So we haven't even
processed it all.

00:46:08.160 --> 00:46:09.940
And Planet Hunters
is this great project

00:46:09.940 --> 00:46:13.260
where-- yeah, you go through
and everything's automated is

00:46:13.260 --> 00:46:14.570
what I'm saying for Kepler.

00:46:14.570 --> 00:46:15.470
So much of it is
just algorithmic,

00:46:15.470 --> 00:46:16.830
where it's like
you flag something.

00:46:16.830 --> 00:46:18.680
OK, maybe this is of
interest, goes in this bin.

00:46:18.680 --> 00:46:19.971
Oh, it's not, goes in this bin.

00:46:19.971 --> 00:46:24.200
Well, algorithms are imperfect,
and they don't always

00:46:24.200 --> 00:46:25.740
catch things that human eyes do.

00:46:25.740 --> 00:46:28.986
And so Planet Hunters,
volunteers go through,

00:46:28.986 --> 00:46:30.610
and they look through
the light curves,

00:46:30.610 --> 00:46:31.901
tag things that look promising.

00:46:31.901 --> 00:46:34.110
And actually, they
recently discovered

00:46:34.110 --> 00:46:35.940
a seven-planet system.

00:46:35.940 --> 00:46:38.190
That's, I think, maybe the
second seven-planet system,

00:46:38.190 --> 00:46:40.877
maybe even the first
that Kepler has found.

00:46:40.877 --> 00:46:42.460
And that was through
volunteer effort,

00:46:42.460 --> 00:46:43.620
and I think there's a
huge potential for that.

00:46:43.620 --> 00:46:45.940
But I just want to say,
the other half of that

00:46:45.940 --> 00:46:48.510
is that I think we can't
get too kind of lost

00:46:48.510 --> 00:46:51.030
in the woods of thinking about
like Kickstarter-like stuff.

00:46:51.030 --> 00:46:53.510
Because volunteer work is
great, and that kind of activity

00:46:53.510 --> 00:46:55.760
is great, where you're sifting
through data and stuff.

00:46:55.760 --> 00:47:00.710
I'm a little more not so wild
about the notion that we're all

00:47:00.710 --> 00:47:03.170
going to Kickstarter fund
like a big space telescope

00:47:03.170 --> 00:47:04.490
to find other Earths.

00:47:04.490 --> 00:47:06.010
Just because like,
I mean, how often

00:47:06.010 --> 00:47:08.182
does a $5 billion
Kickstarter program happen?

00:47:08.182 --> 00:47:09.640
And the other
question is like, you

00:47:09.640 --> 00:47:12.801
know, it's kind of an
abdication of what we-- I mean,

00:47:12.801 --> 00:47:15.300
the biggest Kickstarter thing,
the biggest crowdfunded thing

00:47:15.300 --> 00:47:18.630
we have is what we
pay in taxes, right?

00:47:18.630 --> 00:47:20.755
I mean, NASA, in a
way, is crowdfunded.

00:47:20.755 --> 00:47:22.330
It's funded by us.

00:47:22.330 --> 00:47:25.140
So I think that if you're
just either resorting

00:47:25.140 --> 00:47:27.180
to the beneficence
of billionaires

00:47:27.180 --> 00:47:30.570
to do this or the
crowd, well, you're

00:47:30.570 --> 00:47:33.200
really missing the fact that,
well, what is NASA doing?

00:47:33.200 --> 00:47:36.070
And then you have to question,
what is NASA's purpose?

00:47:36.070 --> 00:47:38.880
So I think that before we get
on the bandwagon of that kind

00:47:38.880 --> 00:47:40.610
of thing, we have
to really consider

00:47:40.610 --> 00:47:41.715
what we already
have on the table.

00:47:41.715 --> 00:47:42.673
AUDIENCE: Well, thanks.

00:47:46.149 --> 00:47:48.190
LEE BILLINGS: Well, it's
been a lot of fun, guys.

00:47:48.190 --> 00:47:49.316
Is there anymore questions?

00:47:49.316 --> 00:47:50.564
We can always talk afterwards.

00:47:50.564 --> 00:47:52.030
I know that everyone's
probably got

00:47:52.030 --> 00:47:53.196
other things they got to do.

00:47:53.196 --> 00:47:55.600
So thanks.

